Here's a complete implementation:

**Program.cs** (relevant sections):

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Configure max request body size (10MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 10 * 1024 * 1024;
});

builder.Services.AddAntiforgery();

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseAntiforgery();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    // Validate content type
    string[] allowed = ["image/jpeg", "image/png"];
    if (!allowed.Contains(file.ContentType))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are allowed.");

    // Validate size (defense-in-depth alongside Kestrel limit)
    const long maxSize = 10 * 1024 * 1024;
    if (file.Length > maxSize)
        return Results.BadRequest("File exceeds 10MB limit.");

    // Ensure uploads directory exists
    var uploadsPath = Path.Combine(app.Environment.ContentRootPath, "uploads");
    Directory.CreateDirectory(uploadsPath);

    // Generate safe filename to prevent path traversal
    var ext = Path.GetExtension(file.FileName).ToLowerInvariant();
    var fileName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{ext}";
    var filePath = Path.Combine(uploadsPath, fileName);

    await using var stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Create);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName });
})
.DisableAntiforgery(); // Remove this line if you want CSRF protection on this endpoint

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** rejects oversized requests at the server level before buffering.
- **Content-type check** restricts to JPEG/PNG.
- **`Guid` filename** prevents path traversal and collisions.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — remove it if clients will send the antiforgery token (e.g., Razor pages). Keep it for external API clients using bearer auth instead.

If you're behind IIS, also add to `web.config`:

```xml
<system.webServer>
  <security>
    <requestFiltering>
      <requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="10485760" />
    </requestFiltering>
  </security>
</system.webServer>
```
